\begin_layout Subsubsection
Budget Constraint
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Income - 1200.
 Fish, Mango prices - 4, 1 respectively.
 What's the budget constraint?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Max amount of fish, mangos ? 300, 1200 respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The budget constraint is: 
\begin_inset Formula $4F+M=1200$
\end_inset

.
 The cost equals the income.
 Graph plot is a negative-slope straight line, crossing 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 axes at the max mangos / fish points.
 Any point on the curve or beneath it is a possible consumption bundle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Slopes
\series default
 of curves always have meaning in economics.
 How many mangos should be given up to buy extra fish? The 
\series bold
relative
\series default
 price of fish is 4 mangos (denoted not in money, but in other products).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Preferences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now after dealing with what the consumer 
\series bold
can
\series default
 afford, we deal with what he 
\series bold
wants
\series default
.
 Being rational, the costomer prefers the bundle which gives him the highest
 level of satisfaction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

More is better than less
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 However, when comparing (2,4) to (4,3) - the decision depends on the consumer,
 which requires some tool to compare bundles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Indifference
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Curves Consumption bundles that give the consumer same level of utility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I.Cs are always downward sloping (that would contradict 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

more is better than less
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), the same logic rules out a horizontal/vertical consumption curve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Higher I.Cs are preferred to lower ones.
 Given 2 curves, how do we know that? Using transitivity, with a slope connectin
g from (0,0) - if 
\begin_inset Formula $A>B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A=C$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $C>B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I.Cs cannot cross, which would contradict 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

more better than less
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I.Cs are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

thin
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (they cannot be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

thick
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, that would violate the basic assumption as well).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
MRS
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(Marginal
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Rate
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Substitution) The rate, at which a customer is willing to trade one good
 for another
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In other words: How many mangos can be given up for a single fish, to keep
 indifferent? Contrary to the budget line, the slope here is not constant.
 The more you have of some product - the less you value it, thus the MRS
 normally falls as moving along the I.C (it's convex and not concave).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is possible, in theory, for the I.Cs to be concave, but it's quite unlikely
 (it requires that the willingness to trade increases as you have less of
 some product).
 Thus it's uncommon but doesn't contradict rationality (he would end up
 spending all budget on one good).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Utility Representation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $U(x,y)$
\end_inset

 assigns a numerical value for each bundle, representing satisfaction /
 benefit level of consuming it.
 Given it, we can determine what will be the consumer decision.
 The rational consumer would choose the optimal affordable bundle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Optimal bundle means one that maximizes the utility level, thus it must
 be on the highest possible indifference curve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A typical solution is the intersection point of the budget line with the
 highest possible I.C.
 At that point the I.C is (usually) tanget to the budget line (
\begin_inset Formula $MRS=-P_{X}/P_{Y}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Generalizing to a formal math equation, we need to find the endogenous variables
 
\begin_inset Formula $X,Y$
\end_inset

 given the exogenous 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{X},P_{Y},I$
\end_inset

.
 Total differential of 
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

U along and indifference curve yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dU=0=\frac{\partial U}{\partial X}dX+\frac{\partial U}{\partial Y}dY\rightarrow MRS=\frac{dY}{dX}=-\frac{MU_{x}}{MU_{y}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $MU_{x},MU_{y}$
\end_inset

 - marginal utilities.
 That's the mathematical description of a particular indifference curve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $FOC:|MRS(X,Y)|=P_{X}/P_{Y}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The budget line equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two conditions are needed, because there're 2 variables in the solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A utility function is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $U=F^{0.6}M^{0.4}$
\end_inset

, prices are 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{F},P_{M}$
\end_inset

, income is 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 What's the optimal choice?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tangency condition:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|MRS|=\frac{0.6F^{-0.4}M^{0.4}}{0,4F^{0.6}M^{-0.6}}=\frac{3M}{2F}=\frac{P_{F}}{P_{M}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The budget line is: 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{F}F+P_{M}M=I$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M=0.4I/P_{M}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=0.6I/P_{F}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that in this form of utilify function, the amount of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 doesn't depend on the price of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 (unlike some other utility functions).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Demand Function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution for each endogenous variable is a function os all exogenous
 variables.
 When the consumer maximizes utilisy, it's calles the 
\series bold
demand function for X
\series default
.
 It describes the desired (optimal) quality of a certain product.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Determinants of Demand
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Preferences
\series default
: As the consumer prefers the product more (more utility by consuming it),
 quantity demand increases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Income
\series default
: As it increases, the consumer wll consume more if the good is normal,
 but less if it's inferior (i.e hamburger: Why? - Because there're more expensive
 alternatives).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Related Good Price
\series default
: If the price on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 increases, the demand on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 might increase (if they're substitutes, like apple/orange juice) or decrease
 (if they're complements, like coffee+milk).
\end_layout

